column11: Uhuru Kenyatta was declared the winner of Kenya's August presidential elections, however, Kenyatta's opponent Raila Odinga challenged the results and the Supreme Court declared them invalid (Washington Post). A rerun election is planned for October 2017. Kenya's constitution allows petitioners to challenge the results of an election at the Supreme Court seven days after the date of the declaration of the results of the presidential election. Correcting forecast. I expect Odinga to challenge if Kenyatta is declared the winner as seems likely. His whole strategy is to claim that the electoral commission is biased against him, and his withdrawal was intended to force a change. He won't accept a walkover victory for Kenyatta. The election could also be declared void, which is what Odinga may have been gambling on, but observers don't seem to be expecting that.

Now that Odinga has dropped out there is no serious candidate to oppose Kenyatta. I think this means the electoral commission goes ahead with a deeply flawed process, Kenyatta wins easily, and then Odinga challenges his legitimacy in the court again. And the in the end by dropping out Odinga will have secured a moral high ground for himself and that's about it.

I think Kenyatta wins the election in part because I think he probably, or at least possibly, won legitimately the first time. That said, I am also sure that Odinga is going to challenge again, in both the streets and the courts, because he has nothing to lose.

He won fairly comfortably last time, so in the absence of some egregious misbehaviour it's unlikely the court will want to intervene again. Knowing or suspecting that, the opposition will most likely not bother to file a challenge.

- Most western monitors think that the issues with the election were more incompetence than foul play (per The Economist) - Kenyatta won by a lot, even if there were irregularities it seems unlikely that they will result in that large of a swing in the new poll. Plus since his party holds power, they have a significant advantage that comes from that. - Will turnout be lower in a re-run? Hard to quanitfy, but my guess that it will be slightly lower turnout, but probably not as big a collapse as you would see in a western democracy like France. That shouldn't affect the results dramatically. - I think Kenyatta is a massive favorite to win again, I'd guess 80% or more. - Will Odinga challenge in the Supreme Court? Tough to say. I lean No, but this could change significantly depending on how he campaigns the re-poll. I think No because he appeared to take this challenge to the court as a result of western pressure (http://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-40949265), and that pressure will be there to not challenge if he loses again. I'd say 70% likely that if Odinga loses, he doesn't challenge.
